  "prompt": "Why are there no interviews of Garrett Camp?",
  "response": "Garrett Camp, the co-founder of StubHub, Expa, and Uber, is known for maintaining a relatively low public profile. Unlike some other high-profile tech entrepreneurs, Camp tends to avoid extensive media interviews and public appearances. There are a few possible reasons for this:\n\n1. **Privacy Preference**: Camp may prioritize his privacy and prefer to keep a low profile, focusing on his work rather than public attention.\n\n2. **Role at Uber**: While he co-founded Uber, Camp has primarily been involved in the early stages and product development rather than the CEO role or day-to-day operations. Travis Kalanick (and later Dara Khosrowshahi) has been more visible as the face of the company.\n\n3. **Focus on Other Ventures**: Camp is involved in multiple projects, such as Expa, a startup studio that supports new companies. His focus might be on building and advising rather than engaging with the media.\n\n4. **Personal Style**: Some individuals simply prefer to stay out of the spotlight, choosing to let their work speak for itself.\n\n5. **Strategic Communication**: It\u2019s possible that Camp strategically avoids interviews to maintain a specific public image or to prevent misinterpretation of his statements.\n\nWhile there are occasional mentions of Camp in articles or interviews about Uber or Expa, he rarely gives standalone interviews. If you\u2019re looking for insights into his work, you might find more information through Expa\u2019s website or his occasional social media posts.",
